The significance of the observed effect of X on Y, adjusting for Z, was calculated in two different ways. In a traditional zero-order significance test (Eq. 2), the coefficient for the adjusted effect (βXY.Z) is divided by its standard error (SE(βXY.Z)). This gives a T-value and if the corresponding p-value is significant (usually defined as p < 0.05), an independent association between X and Y adjusting for Z is assumed, i.e. it is assumed to differ from zero. In the test accounting for expected adjusted effect (AEAE test), we have, instead, the difference between the observed and the expected, as given by Eq. 1, coefficients for the adjusted effect in the numerator (Eq. 3). Here a significant T-value would indicate that the observed adjusted effect differs from the expected due to spurious reasons.2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
